objects.title: Notes
objects.text: Enables the display of various notes throughout the CYOA. Opens a sub-menu.

objects.title: Information
objects.text: Toggle notes that provide extra in-world information, context, or explanations.

objects.title: Hints
objects.text: Will toggle the display of hints to obtain any relevant hidden combos or sub-menus.

objects.title: Warning
objects.text: Toggle notes that provide warnings about possible misunderstandings of various options.

objects.title: Author's Notes
objects.text: Toggle notes from the author of the CYOA. May roast your decisions, provide narrative insights to choosing various options, or just random thoughts. May break narrative flow.

objects.title: Drop-In
objects.text: It looks like you are keeping your own body and will brave the tower as you are. Be careful who you share your secret with.

objects.title: Reincarnation
objects.text: You will be leaving your old body behind to take one specially provided for your new adventure.

objects.title: Towerborn
objects.text: You originate from inside the Tower on one of its many floors. Even if you are born in the tower, Headon may overlook you if you lack the potential to climb the tower or play into one of his many schemes.

objects.title: Irregular
objects.text: You originate from outside the Tower. It is uncertain how you managed to get inside the Tower, but you will find yourself before Headon on the First Floor where he will determine your potential to climb the tower. This option places you in the same category as Rachel to Baam, or the Family Heads to Zahard.

objects.title: Chosen Irregular
objects.text: There is no doubt about it; you entered the Tower under your own power. Fate will conspire to see your success as you climb the Tower. It is no longer required for you to enter the Tower on the First Floor, though you will have to begin your climb on the Second if you choose to accept Headon's offer. One day you will join the other monsters that have graced the Tower such as Urek, Zahard, and Enryu. Until then, Baam may become a healthy rival or dangerous adversary.

rows.title: Apparent Age
rows.titleText: Your real age isn't as important as how you're perceived based on your apparent age. Young or old, you can still climb the Tower. Your apparent age is linked to your personality/mental age.

rows.title: Races
rows.titleText: Many intelligent species call the Tower home, some common, some uncommon, and some rarer still.

rows.title: Family
rows.titleText:
Your family can have just as much bearing on your public perception as your own abilities and achievements. Everyone knows of the 10 Great Families, but there are also a number of other Special Families that have gained their own standing within the Tower.

While your family lineage may be rich and well-documented, you can choose up to four families to represent the origin of your parents or grandparents.

objects.title: Obscure Family
objects.text: There are simply too many people in the Tower for every family to share the limelight. You are from one of these families and may lack familial ties to any well known families.

objects.title: Special Family
objects.text: While not quite on the level of one of the 10 Great Families, you have been born into or adopted into a family of, still, notable standing. This may also include cadet branches of the 10 Great Families that no longer use the main families' name.

objects.title: Great Family
objects.text: After Zahard and his companions finished their climb, 10 of the Great Warriors settled down and formed their own families. You have the fortune of being born into one or more of these families.

objects.title: Blood of Zahard
objects.text: Depending on your origin, you may be a chosen elite, or you might be a mystery to the Tower at-large. Either way, the blood of King Zahard flows within your veins now.

rows.title: Special Families
rows.titleText:
Your family can have just as much bearing on your public perception as your own abilities and achievements. Everyone knows of the 10 Great Families, but there are also a number of other Special Families that have gained their own standing within the Tower.

While your family lineage may be rich and well-documented, you can choose up to four families to represent the origin of your parents or grandparents.

rows.title: Great Families
rows.titleText:
Your family can have just as much bearing on your public perception as your own abilities and achievements. Everyone knows of the 10 Great Families, but there are also a number of other Special Families that have gained their own standing within the Tower.

While your family lineage may be rich and well-documented, you can choose up to four families to represent the origin of your parents or grandparents.

rows.title: Progress
rows.titleText: Choose where you are in your climb to the top.

rows.title: Regular Progress
rows.titleText: You are still a regular and climbing the Tower. The options below determine your status as a Regular. The higher the rank, the more options you have available for your location setting later. Your rank will also correlate to your general strength and level of abilities.

objects.title: F-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have begun their climb on the Second Floor. This rank isn't official until the Floor's tests are successfully passed. Failing the tests of a Floor while an F-Rank Regular will cause you to lose your position as a Regular and the right t climb the Tower.

objects.title: E-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have passed the tests of the 20th Floor earn this rank. Regulars of this rank gain the security in being able to fail subsequent tests without losing the right to climb the Tower.

objects.title: D-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have pass the tests of the 30th Floor.

objects.title: C-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have passed the C-Rank Regular Test somewhere between floors 49 and 51.

objects.title: B-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have passed the B-Rank Regular Test somewhere between Floors 78 and 82.

objects.title: A-Rank
objects.text: Regulars that have passed the A-Rank Regular Test somewhere between Floors 117 and 123.

objects.title: Sponsored
objects.text: The Great Families or Special Families may sponsor special Regulars, affording them support and resources out of reach of the common Regular. However this may result in having to meddle in affairs on behalf of a sponsoring family to work around Rankers being unable to interfere in the progress of a Regular's climb.

rows.title: Ranker Progress
rows.titleText:
Congratulation, you have climbed to the 134th Floor and passed its tests. The Ranker Administration Office has officially given you a rank. Your rank represents a combination of your power, recognition, and influence. While it's possible for one to achieve a higher rank with just the latter two metrics, it is safest to assume that a higher rank implies a stronger Ranker.

There are around 100,000 Rankers in the Tower. Your Rank will indicate where you fall within this number of other Rankers. Rankers are considered to be Advanced Rankers once they reach a rank of 10,000 or less, and represent the top 10% of all Rankers. High Rankers represent the top 1% of all Rankers, and thus hold ranks 1,000 or less.

Your Rank is not fixed and can change through out your lifetime for any number of reasons.

objects.title: Common Ranker
objects.text: You fall within the most common set of Rankers encountered in the Tower. While there may not be too much special about you compared to another Ranker, you outclass nearly all Regulars in all capacities.

objects.title: Advanced Ranker
objects.text: You have reached elite status as a Ranker. Few will find the ability to best you in whatever you choose to specialize in. Only other Advanced Rankers or High Rankers will pose much threat to you; Regulars certainly won't.

objects.title: High Ranker
objects.text: You have reached the point that some consider you a god among gods. To other Rankers your presence will be comparable to a calamity. As a High Ranker, you also are able to become the Ruler of a Floor, should a vacancy appear.

objects.title: Blue Hole
objects.text: The term Blue Hole is given to High Rankers who have been inactive for such a long period of time that the Ranker Administration Office no longer knows of their status. It is unknown if they are still alive or dead, and their true influence and power is hard to measure. Whatever rank you choose will represent the rank you held before you became a Blue Hole.

rows.title: Shinsu
rows.titleText:
Shinsu is the divine water that flows through everything in the Tower. It is essential to all life in the Tower. Strong or weak, ranker or regular, running out of shinsu is a death sentence.

Produced by the Tower, shinsu cannot run out or be completely consumed. It responds to thought, motion, and willpower, which forms the basis of manipulation and control techniques. Shinsu can take the place of any other particle and perform the same function while still fundamentally being shinsu. This allows for shinsu to be integrated into items and technology, and ultimately allows for shinsu to do and be anything, given the right circumstances.

Climbing the Tower will see the ambient shinsu having a higher and higher average density. At lower densities it is closer to air or other gasses, while higher densities see it closer to liquids or solids. Low density or concentrated shinsu is invisible to the naked eye and only becomes visible once it reaches a high enough density or is concentrated in a control technique.

Towerborn are required to contract with an Administrator in order to use shinsu on a floor. Shinsu contracts come with defined limits, set in place by the administrator, on the amount of shinsu they may control, regardless of their overall ability or skill. Irregulars that choose to take this contract willingly shackle themselves, as they otherwise have no upper limit to the amount of shinsu they can control.

objects.title: Baang
objects.text: Baangs are a discrete quantification of how much Shinsu someone can manipulate at one time. A Baang is usually seen as a concentrated release of Shinsu. The number of Baangs someone can create is strongly associated with their skill. A skilled individual will, on average, require 4 years to create just one Baang, let alone learning to control it. Less than 10 D-Rank regulars can control more than 3 Baangs, and the average High Ranker can control 30-50 Baangs.

objects.title: Myun
objects.text: Myun is the size of a single Baang and measures the surface area that it spreads across. In general, a larger Myun implies that a larger area can be affected by one's Shinsu. However, having a large Myun does not also imply being able to freely control the density within the Baang; for most a Myun is most dense at its center and tapers off toward the edges. Some have the skill to make the edge of the Myun quite dense, or even freely control the internal density.

objects.title: Soo
objects.text:
Soo refers to the concentration or mass of Shinsu within a Baang. Only the most concentrated part of a Baang is used to measure Soo, and can only be done by lighthouses, observers, or specialized senses. The effectiveness and destructiveness of a Baang increase as the Soo of a Baang increase. Regions with denser environmental Shinsu allows Soo to increase faster, but there is an upper limit to how high it can increase, depending on the individual.

The amount of Soo in a Baang isn't uniform and has a dependency on the Myun, creating large differences between different people who manipulate Shinsu. Those with a higher concentration find it easier to manipulate a higher Soo in smaller Myun, while those that are skilled in distributed data processing have an edge at manipulating more Soo within a large Myun.

objects.title: Tension
objects.text: Tension is a derived quantity representing the density of a Baang. It has a high correlation with the destructiveness of a Baang.

rows.title: Shinsu Manipulation
rows.titleText: Shinsu Manipulation is a more advanced form of direct Shinsu Control. Manipulating Shinsu external to their body can allow one to change the environment, to attack an opponent or to carry out other actions, or manipulate it internally to allow things such as flying or levitation.

objects.title: Plus Tendency
objects.text: For most individuals, increasing any one of the number of Baangs, Myun, or Soo results in a decrease in the other two quantities. Increasing the number of Baangs results in smaller and less dense Baangs; Baangs that are larger are less numerous and dense; and highly dense Baangs are few and number and smaller. This phenomenon is known as the Minus Tendency. Most Shinsu wielders can train or use equipment to mitigate the effects of being a Minus. However, in rare cases, one can be born with the ability to increase all three quantities simultaneously. This is known as having the Plus Tendency.

addons.title: Note:
addons.text: Having a Plus Tendency doesn't mean being able to generate infinite Baangs or the like. One is still limited by the maximum they can achieve in any of the three quantities.

objects.title: Flow Control
objects.text: Shinsu naturally flows in various directions on its own. Flow Control allows one to accelerate the flow of Shinsu in a particular direction. The faster one drives Shinsu to flow, the harder it is to stop. Flow Control improves one's ability to manipulate larger quantities of Shinsu.

objects.title: Reverse-Flow Control
objects.text: Reverse-flow Control, as it's name would imply, involves decelerating the flow of Shinsu. Reverse-flow Control is often used defensively and can be used to stop or destroy an enemy or their Shinsu. Reverse-flow Control requires being able to sense the flow of Shinsu more accurately than regular Flow Control. Filling a sealed room with Shinsu can make it vastly easier to perform Reverse-flow Control by increasing the filled density.

objects.title: Body Reinforcement
objects.text: Body Reinforcement involves manipulating the internal flow of Shinsu within one's body. It can be used to heal oneself or others, enhance physical abilities, or granting other esoteric abilities. Manipulating the flow of Shinsu beyond the means of the body is dangerous and can lead to death if used improperly (or offensively).

objects.title: Shinsu Quality
objects.text:
When Shinsu is flowed in particular ways, it can develop qualities that mimic natural phenomena such as heat, light, etc. When Shinsu behaves as one of these phenomena, it is said to have a quality.

It is rare to have the ability to manipulate Shinsu one controls into having a quality, but qualities that match the controller can be made into Baangs easier and made to be denser. It is possible for individuals to have multiple Shinsu Qualities, but this would have compounding rarity.

Shinsu Qualities can be manifested externally or internally.
